I had NO idea that irritability was a sign of anxiety or depression when I was in the thick of it.

My kids were SO little...& there were so freaking many of them! 3 in diapers, breastfeeding back to back, no sleep... 

I'd get flustered &sweaty & overwhelmed & then I'd just snap. Jump up & start ranting about the mess, speed tidying to keep the tears at bay. Don't touch me. Don't talk to me. Why is everything so hard? Why does nobody help? I'm alone! I'm an awful mom! I can't do this!

I'd eventually tire myself out, calm myself down...& I would be so ashamed. Why am I like this? God, I'm a nightmare. 

In retrospect it's easy to see... but when you're drowning in it, all you know is that the light on the surface is getting further & further away. 

This still happens, especially when we're in a hurry or I'm feeling overwhelmed with work. I look around my cluttered house with sticky fingerprints & half filled little-boy water cups & I start to panic. It's too much. It's all piling up! I have too much work, too many bills, too much clutter, too little time & too little sleep. All the things that were a whisper in the background become screams, demanding attention.
It's enough to crush me on any given day, at any given moment. 

It does eventually pass. I've learned to make my little lists, take my deep breaths, do my silly counting. I hug my babies & apologize for being so cranky. & then we move on, back to taking things one at a time. 

Just because I can't juggle it all perfectly doesn't mean I'm failing. As a solo mama with too many jobs, some things aren't going to be the way I wish they were. My house, my hair, my laundry pile. It's a conscious choice I'm having to make, to let go of that shit in exchange for a crumb of peace. Stressing over it won't make my days longer or my dishes wash themselves. & acknowledging THAT fact doesn't make the stress or anxiety stop...even though I wish it did.

So I give myself a million cheesy Tony Robbins pep talks a day & have a standing warning to my friends that my house WILL be messy, should they come visit. 
& really, that's the best I can do...even if everyone still totally pisses me off, from time to time.

Coming out the other side of the holidays, exhausted& broke as hell, we're one of the many families blessed with a birthday soon after! It creeps up on me every year, this being no exception. Scrimping & scrambling to make it fucking magical while I'm hangin' on with nothing but my comfiest(&kinda gross) robe & a prayer. 

I was running over the plan for the birthday tomorrow, thinking little man would be excited..when he hits me with;
 "Oh. But... I want to bring 3 friends to the movies. & I didn't even get as many Robux as I told you I wanted for Christmas. So will that be added to my presents?"

It felt like a kick to the gut. I know that Id have had a passionate reaction to this scenario, pre-kids. Hell no, ya little shit! Not good enough? Then you get nothing!

But me now? I just feel defeated & tired.

I want to be able to give them everything they want. The big bday parties, the STUPID expensive hoodie that annoying YouTube guy wears. But i can't. 

I want to protect them from having to worry about adult things or knowing how scary it gets sometimes. To let them be kids, with little kid worries!

 But damn...they really don't get it. They don't see it?

This isn't a happy post, with a synapsis of a grand lesson that was learned at the end. At this point, I'm just trying to figure it out. 
My kids are AMAZING. Wonderful & loving. But have I failed them? Failed to teach them gratitude & grace? Shown them to feel entitled & expectant?

I'll be done with my pity-party in a sec. Thnx for letting me vent. I'm sure some of you will judge, & and I get it! I might have judged at some point, too. But maybe there's a couple of you that have also encountered your kid being an ungrateful little dink & wondered how you had gotten there..

Maybe the truth at the end of the day is... it's all a part of the learning.
 Life, love & maybe helping out at the 🍲 kitchen now & then is all that's needed? I don't know. I friggin hope so. But for now...this pep talk is for me & for you, in case it helps. Repeat as needed♡

You're amazing. You're doing your great & those around you see it. Sometimes, even the BEST kids are just a bit asshole-ish! But they'll be OK.& so will you.🫶

I used to be super social! Loved being around people, going out. That changed after having kids, like it does for so many of us. Taking 3 little boys SO close in age ANYWHERE is almost 0% fun & 100% chaos & tantrums.
So we'd go to the playground, or I'd go out with my girls every couple of months, but that was about it.

Then covid happened. Life exploded, everything changed.& somewhere along the way, I became completely contented with never leaving my house.
& that scares me. That's not me.

I'll make plans with people that I genuinely love & enjoy, then spend the time leading up to it dreading it & thinking of all the reasons I shouldn't go. Then I usually don't. Go, I mean.

This night pictured was no different. I didn't want to let my friend down, I wanted her to know that I still love her despite how little she sees of me. I didn't want to upset her, or screw up her night. But that dizzy, sweaty feeling was starting to hit me...the specific brand of hell + nausea that I have understood as "physical symptoms of stress" since my C-PTSD diagnosis. That feeling knocks me on my ass... but subsides once the threat (plans) is managed (canceled)
So, of course, I texted my friend & told her I wasn't feeling well, had lots to do, & didn't think I could make it.
She replied, "I don't care, you're coming."
This caught me off guard, just enough to do as I was told! I put on a bra & whatever wasn't ugly or too tight, got in my car...& just fucking went.

In this instance...I was SO glad that I did. It was relaxed, super fun, not overwhelming, didn't last too late. & while that outcome isn't always the case, I desperately needed to know that it COULD be. That it was still important that I try; not just for me, but for the people that care about me.

I'm not sure how to fix this, or how to make it better. But i DO know that you might see a lot of yourself in what I'm battling right now...& if that's the case, I thought you should know that YOU are worth fighting for too. Keep trying, friend ♡ it WILL get better.

Women have gotten me through things in my lifetime that would have (& almost did) otherwise killed me. My love for women has only grown in motherhood and has bled into a growing love for myself as well. As a mom to 3 little boys, I hope to raise aware, respectful, strong, outspoken young men who stand with women in the fights that are still needed. 

Life as a woman in Canada is amongst the easiest and most privileged. Though I'm still subject to harassment, assault, violence, pay discrepancy, dismissal, and hatred because of my gender.... I'm not being imprisoned, and mu r d€red for it. It would be remiss to "celebrate" the strength, beauty, and resilience of women today without acknowledging  the atrocities being brought against women internationally. 
JUST BECAUSE IT'S NOT CURRENTLY HAPPENING TO YOU OR SOMEONE YOU KNOW DOESN'T MEAN IT'S NOT HAPPENING!

Denying the repression of women and the need for active feminism just because you don't feel repressed is a betrayal of the sisterhood of women. Your comfort doesn't erase someone else's pain.

So today...let's be so grateful for how far we have come... but not so ignorant and removed that we don't speak out about HOW MUCH FIGHTING we still have left! 
We're with you, our Iranian sisters.

This will ALWAYS be one of my very favourite pictures.... not because it's cute (which it is), but because it ensures that I'll never forget THIS feeling. Of being loved so completely, and with such vigor, that the only way it can be expressed is with face smooshing. 

Tiny, chubby, sticky fingers tangled through my hair. Little baby lips, sweet chunky cheeks, slobber, and probably some boogz, all mashed up against my face because he loves me so much he can't help himself. 🥹

Even the most precious moments that I swore I'd never forget have started to fade. I can still see them, just at the edges of my memory....blurred and slipping. It's one thing i wasn't prepared for because while you're in the throws of parenting small children, it's all-encompassing. You think the "other side" of it is light-years away and that these long, intense days that have made such an impact are seared into you forever. 

And they are, for the most part...
But those delicious details aren't. They're the first to go, making room for swimming lessons schedules, and when to RSVP to that Connor kids' birthday party. The sweetest morsels hold their ground as best they can, but without reminders, they get covered in dust and tucked away, like the rest of the pages that bind together our lives. 

This picture, though. Taken after a mommy-day-away, being greeted by my cherub, spitsnotting me as a mark of pure love...
It's making sure that this moment is one that I won't forget. I'm so grateful I could cry.

Enjoy the moments, be present... but don't forget to take the pictures. To get IN the pictures. 

...and to also print them off into photo books or something. 
Just in case.

Near the end of my 3rd pregnancy, i was desperate to give birth. Mostly to bypass the intense in-between stage of the unknown..

I was home alone with a 1 year old, a 2 year old, and an aching body. Convinced I'd be going into labor by myself, with my other babies watching in horror. As the days leading up to the "due date" came and went, my anxiety was sky high. 
I finally booked myself in for acupuncture. I wanted the practitioner to hit whatever magical buttons I had that would just help me get through this. 

But she didn't. Instead, she simply asked, "Are you afraid of having this baby?"

I was taken aback. I'm here, aren't I?!

Yet being asked that question suddenly gave me permission to acknowledge what I had been afraid to even admit to myself. 
I was fucking terrified. 

25 years old, 3 babies under the age of 3, mostly on my own. I didn't know how I was getting by each day as it was, and couldn't imagine adding a newborn into the mix. I couldn't actually picture my day to day life with this baby, whom I already loved more than life itself.

Turns out it was me holding him in. 
I had desperately needed a safe space to express my fears, my worries & my doubts. To be heard & held & told that life would go on; that I wasn't alone.

As mothers, we carry the weight of the world on our shoulders, in the truest sense. We carry our families, keeping every appointment detail, laundry schedule, eating preference,  even the tiniest swings in our baby's moods. We keep it all in our minds, 24/7, adjusting our days and our beings accordingly. To show up & BE everything for everyone.
Yet we're expected to do so with a smile of enthusiasm & contentedness. Embrace the role as our life's purpose & move through motherhood with ease. If we DONT, then that must mean... we're horrible mothers who don't love our children.
Right? 

We're all quietly telling ourselves the same story & perpetuating our own societal cages. The only way to break out is...to talk. To each other, openly, honestly, & with compassion for ourselves & our peers. No shame. No judgment. Just truth, tears, swears, & camaraderie. 

Thanks for being my safe space. ❤️

I remember taking this photo a year and a half ago. Looking at it after snapping it and feeling so awkward. Silly. Why is my mouth like that? Does my nose really look like that? I'm such a try-hard, so embarrassing. 

A year and a half ago isn't a very long time! Yet, when I saw this photo today for the first time since, I had a much different reaction.
Oh, I looked pretty! Man, I should cut my hair again. I've gained weight since then. I should have appreciated looking good while I had the chance!
Etc, etc, etc...

My brain lied to me then... and as much as I don't believe it at this moment, I'm trying to accept that my brain is lying to me now. 
As women, especially, we're trained and molded in the most painfully contradicting way. Be pretty, but don't try. Be confident, but know your place. Love yourself, but still make sure to put others' needs first. "Know your worth," but make sure to discount it. Don't be insecure or needy, it's annoying. Don't be so confident and secure; ugh, you're so stuck up!

So... I wanted to post this today for a couple of reasons. 
1) because I look cuuuuuteeee 🥰
2) need to get more of that lash serum!

3) because I want the reminder. That woman looked at herself then and saw an awkward, grubby, chubby imposter. She saw the lie and fully believed it. Just the same as I see that same lie now, in my mirror. The reminder I'm cherishing in this photo is the realization that it truly IS a lie... then, and now. 

Just one more step (of many) in deprogramming the hater in my noggin! Slowly but surely bonking that lil twerp on the head until she's kaput...and I'm in my bad bitch, self-love Era. 💃

Women are expected to be readily available, sacrificing themselves for every need &whim of their family over their own, & be HAPPY about it. Always. 
We DO sacrifice so much of ourselves for our families. & we do it lovingly, &willingly, &consistently. BUT... we feel many emotions surrounding this aspect of motherhood that aren't always happiness. 
How fucking weird would it be if we were ALWAYS happy about being woken up at 430 AM to someone else pissing the bed? About having to take care of everyone else on YOUR sick day, when all you want to do is be tucked in, kissed on the forehead, & left alone? 

We're TIRED. We're lonely. We're frustrated. We're lost. We're confused. We're angry. We're bitter. We're ashamed. We're joyful. We're terrified. We're anxious. We're overwhelmed by duty h by love.

Despite the constant weight of ALL of it, we still show up & do the things. Because that's what moms DO. 
But in all of the glory & dismissal of motherhood, we have somehow been pigeonholed into an expectation that we never agreed to.
Erasing ourselves entirely into our role. Devoting our every moment to our families & children, taking none for ourselves.

That's insane.
TRULY fucking nutbarz.

Excellent mothers go for a run. Excellent mothers put their kids in daycare. Excellent mothers shut the door while having a shower. They go out dancing with their friends, they take pottery classes, they go to the movies alone. & most of the excellent mothers that DO those things, despite the shame & guilt & whispers, do them because they have been the excellent mother that DIDN'T. The excellent mother who suffocated in her duties & nearly drowned in the needs of her loved ones. She came back up for air, realizing that next time she may not make it. & that her kids NEED her. So even when she couldn't or wouldn't take that time for herself & her own needs, she would for her kids. Because they deserve to have their Mommy, with her light intact. 

In case you needed the reminder: YOUR KIDS DONT NEED YOU 24/7! Even if they WANT ONLY you, they'll survive you taking a break.
Don't abandon those parts of your life that you love. Go fill your cup, miss your babies & come back recharged

This hit the feels. As parents, we're just doing our very best. And the very best for each of us, in each unique situation, is different. Sometimes, our babies deserve more than our best. And sometimes, they don't recognize what was best for them wasn't what they wanted. 
But when we become parents ourselves...when we hold our babies in our arms and feel the debilitating love and fear sweep through our veins, knowing now what our parents meant when they said "you'll understand when you have kids of your own"...
Our parents are just people. They're not all-knowing. They're not super, they're not perfect. And neither are we. But God damn, if it's the way it's supposed to be... they love us. And no matter what I didn't get, as a kid... no matter what ripples I have dealt with over the years, what amends needed to be made, what apologies and cracks needed to be addressed, I get it now. 

My babies deserve better than what I can give them. They deserve EVERYTHING. But the reality is, they get ME. So I'm gonna pull myself up by my bootstraps, and I'm gonna make damn sure that I'm enough for them, in all the ways that I can be. 

It's hard, sometimes. When life is kicking my ass, I'm exhausted; working 3 jobs and sleeping less than I did when they were newborns. I catch myself getting grumpy at their lack of awareness. They're so relaxed, enjoying their games and their friends and their food and their warm beds, with no second thought, and often even without much appreciation. 

Until I remember... they deserve this time. They deserve this childhood. And I can give it to them. So I'm gonna keep busting my ass to make it last as long as possible. And one day, much like this young man speaking to his Dad, they too will "get it." And they'll know how hard it must have been. And they'll know that their parents pushed through, kept their heads down, and made it work because we LOVE them.
 
I'm not a perfect parent. Not even close. But they'll never have to feel alone or wonder if they're loved. 
My parents gave me that gift, too. One I'll always cherish, and one I'm grateful to be passing down.

Me 11 years ago: whoopsie daisy 👦👦👦 
Friends now: *posts picture of 2 pairs of shoes with another little one in the middle*

But really, all jokes aside, it's kinda wild how different pregnancy and new motherhood has been viewed and supported, even just in the almost 11 years since I did it! 
I was among the first of my friends to have babies, and it was extremely isolating. I was very much on my own and even lost a fair few friends. 
Not through fault, but from a lack of understanding and awareness of what women go through upon entering motherhood. Becoming a mom at such a young age, with 3 back to back, I lived in fight or flight, in a daze, and on exhausted autopilot until just recently!

So glad to see some things changing; slowly, but in the right direction! Thinking about how our mothers (and all of the mothers before them) were treated during birth and postpartum breaks my heart. 
Birth trauma is SO REAL, and affects so many women for the rest of their lives, with no real outlet, solution, or support.
Keep talking, supporting, and advocating for women and mothers! The life bringers deserve transparency and community at every age and every stage 🫶

My parents have introduced my brother, my kids & I to some pretty cool things over the years...
Rock climbing (actual mountains), dog sledding out to isolated cabins in feet of snow, even Flying a plane! They'd wake us up in the middle of the night if one of our farm animals was in labor, letting us bundle up and huddle quietly in the corner of the barn to witness new life being born. So many cool experiences that I didn't realize were as incredible as they are until I was an adult...
And even more so knowing that money wasn't in abundance. Those experiences were FOUGHT for, and earned for us.

Man. How great would it be to have had the awareness that only time and hindsight can offer while we were younger...
Grateful to have realized how cool my folks are, even if it took me a while. To think I ever whined about doing any of that cool shit?!
